# 🚀 Microservices Setup Guide

## 📥 Step 0: Pre Requisites
# 1. MS SQL
# 2. Docker Desktop


# Follow these simple steps to clone, build, and run the entire microservices system using Docker and Maven.
## 📥 Step 1: Clone All Repositories

# Make sure to clone **all the required repositories** into the same root directory.
# ```bash
# git clone <repository-url-1>
# git clone <repository-url-2>
# # ...repeat for all microservices
# ````


## 📦 Step 2: Install Dependencies

# Navigate to each service directory and run:
# ```bash
# mvn clean package
# ```
# ✅ **Note:** Some IDEs or extensions (like VS Code or IntelliJ) can do this step automatically.

---

## 🐳 Step 3: Run All Microservices with Docker

# Make sure Docker is installed and running.
# Run the following command **from the root directory** to start all services using Docker Compose:

# ```bash
 <!-- docker compose -f be-registery/docker-compose.yml -f be-api-gateway/docker-compose.yml -f be-auth-user/docker-compose.yml -f be-auth-user/docker-compose.db.yml -f be-notify-audit/docker-compose.yml -f be-notify-audit/docker-compose.db.yml -f be-auth-user/docker-compose.kafka.yml -f be-auth-user/docker-compose.seeder.yml up --build -->
# ```

# ---

## 🛠️ Step 4: Create Docker Network (if not already created)

# Before running services, ensure the Docker network exists:

# ```bash
# docker network create microservice-network
# ```

---

## 🗄️ Step 5: Connect to the Database (Optional)

# To connect manually to the SQL Server instance, use:
# bash
# sqlcmd -S 127.0.0.1,1434 -U SA -P "Click@123RaoHammad*1"

# > Make sure to use the correct port and credentials as configured in your Docker Compose files.

## 🌐 Accessing the Services

# | Feature          | URL/Port                                                                       | Description                        |
# | ---------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------ | ---------------------------------- |
# | 🧭 Eureka Server | [http://localhost:8671](http://localhost:8671)                                 | View registered microservices      |
# | 📨 Kafka UI      | [http://localhost:8088](http://localhost:8088)                                 | Monitor Kafka messages & consumers |
# | 📚 Swagger Docs  | [http://localhost:8080/swagger-ui.html](http://localhost:8080/swagger-ui.html) | View API documentation via Gateway |

# ---

## ✅ You're All Set!

# All services should now be running. You can:
# * Monitor service registration on Eureka
# * View API documentation on Swagger
# * Inspect messaging activity on Kafka UI

# Happy developing! 🎉